a leaking tank of propane gas ordered out of a 
pennsylvania town was safely emptied here sunday but delaware 
officials complained they never gave permission for the tank to be 
brought into their state 
were very upset because they didnt notify us they planned to 
move it and because of the hour they chose to move it john e 
wilson iii secretary of the state department of natural resources 
and environmental control said sunday 
herm bruce spokesman for the state emergency response team 
said amtrak officials had the tank and its explosive contents moved 
into delaware in the middle of the night an amtrak spokesman said 
the transfer was done after 530 am sunday 
delaware state officials learned of the shipment only because 
fire dispatchers in pennsylvania told their local counterparts 
across the line in delaware that the shipment was en route bruce 
said 
state police then halted four other tanks before they entered 
the state including two that also showed signs of minor leaks he 
said those four tanks were taken to eddystone pa where they 
were to be drained overnight police there said 
bruce stressed that the leaking tank problem was not a serious 
threat 
but residents in a sparsely populated area near the amtrak 
railroad yard here were advised to stay indoors for about five 
hours sunday as workers transferred the propane from the leaking 
tank into an intact one bruce said nearby roads also were closed 
as a precaution 
on friday train traffic was disrupted around ridley park pa 
when the leak in the tank was first discovered interstate 95 
which runs over railroad tracks at the spot the tank and four 
others were being stored also was closed for a time 
the tanks about 50 feet long and 6 feet in diameter are used 
by amtrak to hold propane that fuels heaters during wintertime to 
thaw out track switches said amtrak spokesman clifford black 
it appeared the leak in the one tank was successfully capped 
friday evening black said but another leak was discovered late 
saturday afternoon and once again rail traffic and interstate 
traffic were suspended 
he confirmed that the tank had been transferred to delaware on 
sunday but said he didnt know anything about the charges that 
state officials had not been notified he said the tank left ridley 
park about 530 and arrived in delaware about an hour later 
two of the four tanks that were returned to ridley park have 
small leaks but are not an imminent danger black said sunday 
ridley park fire chief raymond l lonabaugh said saturday that 
he ordered amtrak to remove the leaking tank the tank was 
disconnected from the other tanks and loaded onto a railroad car 
lonabaugh said 
lonabaugh said two amtrak employees were injured friday night 
when they tried to cap the leaking tank without donning protective 
clothing or respirators but black said he didnt know about any 
workers being injured 
