an israeli court on sunday sentenced mordechai 
vanunu the former nuclear technician who spilled his countrys 
atomic secrets to a british newspaper to 18 years in prison for 
treason and espionage 
a threejudge panel announced its sentence in a closeddoor 
session at jerusalems district courthouse shortly after hearing 
sentencing arguments from both sides 
vanunus trial has been shrouded in secrecy since it began in 
september officials said an open trial would harm state security 
the crimes for which vanunu was convicted carry a maximum death 
penalty in israel however prosecutors said earlier they would ask 
for a life sentence which in israel is limited to 20 years the 
court lightened that sentence by two years but its reasons were not 
made public 
according to israeli law vanunu could be released on good 
behavior after 12 years legal commentators said early release was 
unlikely given the nature of vanunus crimes 
defense attorney avigdor feldman said he plans to appeal to 
israels supreme court 
vanunu 34 was convicted last week of treason and espionage for 
telling the sunday times of london israel had nuclear weapons 
a jewishborn convert to christianity vanunu worked for 10 
years at israels nuclear facility in the southern desert town of 
dimona he then left israel smuggling out photographs he took from 
inside the facility 
in october 1986 vanunu handed over the photographs and details 
about israels nuclear program to the sunday times based on his 
information the newspaper reported israel stockpiled the worlds 
sixth largest nuclear arsenal 
israel never responded directly to allegations of its nuclear 
capacity saying only it would not be the first country to 
introduce such weapons into the middle east 
several days after the newspaper published his revelations 
vanunu disppeared from london 
