more than 7000 residents were 
evacuated and 14000 ordered to stay indoors sunday while dutch 
army explosives experts defused a huge bomb from world war ii 
no one was injured in the operation in a densely populated 
residential district life returned to normal after authorities 
removed the bombs ignition shortly after 4 pm 
sundays 315 million operation involved more than 2000 police 
and city officials it was the largest evacuation since 1953 when 
massive floods in the southwestern netherlands killed more than 
1700 people 
at least 14 people were arrested for ignoring the order to stay 
indoors 
authorities also vacated an indoor skating rink to accomodate up 
to 700 pets whose owners insisted on their evacuation but only 
four cats a dog and a handful of birds were taken there said city 
hall spokesman ben van der schaaf 
the 1000pound bomb was dropped by a typhoon bomber of the 
british royal air force on nov 29 1944 during what was meant to 
be a precision raid on the local headquarters of the nazi security 
service or sicherheitsdienst 
the building 500 yards from the site of sundays operation in a 
densely populated innercity district was only slightly damaged in 
the raid and most of the 61 killed were local residents 
the raf bomb tore into a back yard only a few yards from an 
apartment block it was soon forgotten and lay buried more than 30 
feet deep until a resident reminded city hall of its presence 
during renovation work last may 
all residents living within 300 yards of the bomb were 
evacuated police searched their homes to make sure they were 
empty shut off gas and water mains and sealed front doors 
all residents living 300 to 600 yards away were ordered to close 
their doors and windows draw their curtains and stay indoors 
two army explosives experts using a 50yard rope then unscrewed 
the ignition of the 5footlong bomb said their chief maj 
adriaan sprangemeijer 
the tensest moment of the defusing operation came as the pair 
had to leave their heavily armored cabin to pull out the ignition 
with a pair of forceps sprangemeijer said 
