<TEXT>
a prominent arab oil expert describing the 
present oil market as very weak warned sunday that the failure 
of opec members to abide by their output quotas could lead to a 
collapse of oil prices 
abdelaziz alwatari acting secretarygeneral of the 
organization of arab oil exporting countries said a recent arab 
energy conference held in baghdad iraq concluded that the oil 
market is very weak at present because of the absolute slowdown in 
oil demand and because projections of increase in demand have 
failed to come through 
in an interview with the kuwait news agency watari said this 
situation could last for five years he called for a profound 
commitment and high degree of credibility on the part of opec 
states to retain the present reference price of 18 a barrel 
the situation he said also required a high degree of 
cooperation from producers outside the 13nation organization of 
petroleum exporting countries seven of oapecs members including 
influential saudi arabia also are members of opec 
on friday crude oil prices firmed slightly in response to 
reports that members of opecs pricing committee would meet next 
month to discuss ways to stabilize the market 
on the new york mercantile exchange the may contract for west 
texas intemediate the benchmark us crude settled at 1703 per 
barrel up 7 cents from thursdays close 
saudi oil minister hisham nazer on wednesday called for an 
emergency meeting of the pricing committee amid reports some of the 
cartels members have been violating production quotas and prices 
decreed by opec 
the failure of states in opec to stick to the production 
sharing will set the stage for a price decline and any 
extraordinary increase in production could lead to the collapse of 
the price system in the foreseeable future watari warned 
in riyadh nazer discussed cooperation between opec and nonopec 
members with malaysian foreign minister datu alhaj abu alhasan 
ibn alhaj omar whose country is not a member of the cartel 
the official saudi press agency quoted nazer as saying that 
during the meeting the two ministers reviewed the role of 
nonopec producers in helping stabilize the oil market 
